\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Fierce nominalism would explain the existence of \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91universals\u8217\'92 by appealing to the concept of utility or usefulness. It is \u8216\'91useful\u8217\'92 to call two creatures \u8216\'91cats\u8217\'92. It is useful to call two different humans \u8216\'91americans\u8217\'92. \u8220\'93American\u8217\'92 is farily obviously an arbtrary construction - but not so with \u8216\'91cat\u8217\'92. But it is non the less true - if you did not have a useful reason to call two different creatures \u8216\'91cat\u8217\'92, you would not do so. But what is that \u8216\'91useful\u8217\'92 reason? Can we not say that it is useful because it more accurately reflects some universal. No. Because useful is subjective. But there is no way to prove this. It could be that one person\u8217\'92s utility is approximting reality. Especially when we approach scientific terms.}
